Outlier analysis using PCA¶

Recently I tried to detect outliers in some high-dimensional data to find out more about the dataset. It is quite a common task - you have a dataset at your disposal, and you try to learn more about it. One of the very simplest and fastest ways is to use PCA projection:

  • find directions of the largest variance in the data,
  • project the high-dimensional points into 2D plane,
  • plot them and then
  • find records that are not grouped with others visually.

However, when you find these records, you still don't know much about:

  • A) why they are actually outlying, and
  • B) it can be cumbersome to get the record ID from the visual graph.

In this post I solve the first problem by finding the original dimensions that influence the variance the most, and the latter by making use of some cool matplotlib functionality :)

A bit of theory¶

One of the most common way to compute PCA is by using SVD, and take the first two (or three) projections. SVD decomposition is usually noted as

$ \mathbf{A} = \mathbf{U} \mathbf{\Sigma} \mathbf{V}^T $

where $\mathbf{A} \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times m}$ is the original matrix (with many more records $n$ than it's dimension $m$), $\mathbf{U}$ and $\mathbf{V}$ are projecting matrices and $\mathbf{\Sigma}$ is a scaling matrix. There's been much written on these topics, so you can read more about it somewhere else, Wikipedia has a nice article.

Usually SVD decomposition is implemented in such a way that the diagonal singluar values in $\mathbf{\Sigma}$ and the corresponding columns in $\mathbf{V}$ are sorted by the descending variance value.

To compute which dimensions in the original data have the largest "influence" over the data's variance, you can compare the value sizes in each projection. Let's have projected dimension size $dim=2$:

from scipy import linalg
U, S, V = linalg.svd(X, full_matrices=False)
influence = np.abs(np.diag(S[:dim]).dot(V[:dim, :]))
influence /= np.tile(np.sum(influence, axis=1), (influence.shape[1], 1)).T
projected = U[:, :dim]
projected *= S[:dim]

So now influence contains ratios of influence of each of the original dimensions, and projected are the 2D PCA projected points. Neat!

Real-world example¶

Let's work with some real data! I took and obfuscated data from some commodity market. The data contains an order book and a table of realized trades. Order book contains records for each timestamp about the top 20 bids/asks - the prices and their cummulative quantities. Trades are a table of matched asks/bids (they are not contained in the order book). To have a clearer idea:

def plot_table(X, ax):

        ax.plot(order_book.index, order_book["ask%dPrice" % i], color=(0,1-i/top,0))

    ax.plot(trades.index[sellidx], trades.price[sellidx], 'ro')
    plt.ylim([min(order_book["bid%dPrice" % top]),
              max(order_book["ask%dPrice" % top])])

Dimensionality reduction tool¶

This is where dimensionality reduction comes into play. The following class helps a with this problem, the code is somewhat self-explanatory.

The picking magic is done with these lines:

scat = ax1.scatter(self.X_red[:, 0], self.X_red[:, 1],
                c=self.y_colors, s=self.s,
                alpha=0.5, picker=True)      # <-- picker=True
...
fig.canvas.mpl_connect('pick_event', onpick) # <-- event handler
In [21]:
class DimRedPlot:
    """
    Dimensionality reduction tools for jupyter notebook data analysis
    """

    _select_color = '#FF0000'
    def __init__(self, X, y_colors=None, s=30):
        """
        :param X: original data frame that will be reduced
        :param y_colors: label colors for scatter plot (default gray),
                  cannot use red #FF0000 (or _select_color),
                  that is for selected points only
        :param s: reduced points sizes for scatter plot
        """
        self.X = X
        if y_colors is None:
            self.y_colors = np.array(['#DDDDDD'] * len(X))
        else:
            assert self._select_color not in self.y_colors, \
                '%s color isreserved for selected points only' % self._select_color
        if type(s) is not list:
            self.s = [s] * len(X)
        self.picked_points = []
        self.influence = None

        self.X_red, self.influence = self._pca_red(X)

    def _pca_red(self, X):
        """
        Compute the PCA projection and influence of each dimension to the projection
        """
        U, S, V = linalg.svd(X, full_matrices=False)

        influence = np.abs(np.diag(S[:2]).dot(V[:2, :]))
        # normalize
        influence /= np.tile(np.sum(influence, axis=1), (influence.shape[1], 1)).T

        red = U[:, :2]
        red *= S[:2]

        return red, influence

    def create_plot(self, plot_fn, pick_fn):
        """
        Create interactive plot
        :param plot_fn: callable, with arguments plot_fn(X, subplot_ax2)
        :param pick_fn: callable, with arguments plot_fn(X, subplot_ax2, ind)
                        where ind are selected indices
        """
        fig = plt.figure()
        ax1 = fig.add_subplot(211)
        scat = ax1.scatter(self.X_red[:, 0], self.X_red[:, 1],
                    c=self.y_colors, s=self.s,
                    alpha=0.5, picker=True)
        self.picked_points = []

        ax2 = fig.add_subplot(212)
        plot_fn(self.X, ax2)

        def onpick(event):
            ind = event.ind
            self.picked_points.append(ind)
            self.y_colors[ind] = self._select_color
            scat.set_facecolor(self.y_colors)
            pick_fn(self.X, ax2, ind)
            fig.show()

        fig.canvas.mpl_connect('pick_event', onpick)
        plt.tight_layout()
        fig.show()

    def influence_plot(self):
        """
        Plot each dimension with the amount of it's influence
        """
        _, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(2, 1)
        N = self.influence.shape[1]
        ax1.bar(np.arange(N), self.influence[0, :])
        ax1.set_xticks(np.arange(N))
        ax1.set_xticklabels(self.X.columns,fontsize=10, rotation='vertical')
        ax2.bar(np.arange(N), self.influence[1, :])
        ax2.set_xticks(np.arange(N))
        ax2.set_xticklabels(self.X.columns,fontsize=10, rotation='vertical')
        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()

    def outlier_values(self, th= 0.05):
        """
        Return picked outliers with the dimensions that are influential above the threshold
        """
        inf_bool = self.influence > th
        cols = inf_bool[0,:] | inf_bool[1,:]
        points = []
        for add in self.picked_points:
            points += add.tolist()
        return self.X.iloc[points, cols]

That's pretty good for a random setting! Well, I have to admit this demo was little bit optimized for the results, because I know PCA tries to find the largest variance - setting values to smaller ones would not yield such nice results :)

That is not very intelligible. It's hard to compare the results with/without outliers, so let's plot them side by side:

In [36]:
# this is not very nice, but quick&dirty
def plot_influence(X, influence, ax1,ax2, width=0.4, shift_position=0):
    N = influence.shape[1]
    ax1.bar(np.arange(N)+shift_position, influence[0, :], width)
    ax1.set_xticks(np.arange(N))
    ax1.set_xticklabels(X.columns,fontsize=10, rotation='vertical')
    ax2.bar(np.arange(N)+shift_position, influence[1, :], width)
    ax2.set_xticks(np.arange(N))
    ax2.set_xticklabels(X.columns,fontsize=10, rotation='vertical')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    
_, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(2, 1)
plot_influence(pca_red.X, pca_red.influence, ax1,ax2)
plot_influence(pca_outl.X, pca_outl.influence, ax1,ax2, shift_position=0.4)

If you zoom in on some of the columns you can see there are slight differences, but not very many due to the small amount of the introduced outliers.
